But with the Kaiser it is otherwise. This dreamy man of action, this virile mystic, grasps the ee-jret of Japanese power. The magnificent discipline of this Navy and Army, he told his recruits, "springs from patriotism and filial love.” It is the outcome of all that we have oome to recognise in the word “Bashido." "Honorable brothers, let us throw ourselves on the bayonets. Our comrades will take the posi- tion over our bodies.” Whst man with the soul of a Paladin, as has tha Kaiser, ooald toil to have his blood set a-tingle by the heroism of the Japanese major of whom that speech is reported, or to recognise that here is a force before which “mightiest tieeta of iron framed" and “all-shattering guns” are powerless, unless the men whose will they obey are instinct with a like spirit
It is not, however, as brothers-in-arms that William Il.greetsthe Japanese with the salute due to virtue and oonrage. Ra’.har they are the "scourge of God,” as was Attila, and—by a juxtaposition which reveals in a flash his mentality—Napoleon. “Buddha is not superior to our Lord Christ," cries this Crusader of to- day. If the Russians have toiled, it must be that Russian Christianity is in a very bad way; German Christianity is in a bad way also, and the German sovereign doubts whether, "in the event of a war, the Germans would be justified in praying to God for victory.” There is an old-world splendour about this utterance, surprising as it is from the proud ruler of the German peoples, which a materialistic age should not miss. The sovereign who stood on Olivet, clad, so nearly as might be, in the Crusaders’ panoply, and there dreamed his dreams, calls on his soldiers to be even as the knights of old : to watch and prey by their armour, keeping their hearts pure that their strength may be as the strength of ten. The sword of the German Michael must be tem- pered in the armoury of God.
We want to bring home to oar readers the significance of this ntterenoe, so greatly at variance with the tendenoy of modern thought. The grandiose conception of the famous alle- gorieal picture still teems in the Emperor’s brain. The Teuton still stands, in the mujesty of a pare and simple toith, as the protector of he apostate white races against the enemy which cometh in like a flood, as Attila oame before him, from the East. Attila the trembling priests of his time named "the Sconrge of Godbut, later there arose another whom Chriitendom hailed as the "Hammer of God" —Charles Martel, who tamed back the Saraoens from Europe at Tonre. William II., German Emperor, would be the "Hammer of God."

The very sensational news telegraphed from Tokio last evening by Reuter, to the effeot that a German force had occupied Hai-chu, situated on an extensive bay to the northward of the old channel of the Hong-Ho, is, we are glad to see, officially denied from Berlin to-day. Had the very improbable occurrence actually taken place, it would have been difficult to foresee the results to which it would have led. Where there is smoke, however, there is fire, and in the immediate future we can foresee, not only that German policy will be directed might and main to placing obstacles in the way of Japanese success, but alas that when the settlement oomea, it will strive at all hazard to prevent what the Emperor considers dangerous aggrandisement of the destined foe of Christ- endom. That William II. recognises so warmly tho admirable qualities of those whom he regards as a “soourge of God” adds to the perils of the international situation. The revival of the spirit in whioh the Crusaders faced the Paynims will be a new and troubling element in the comfortable world of to-day. The remarkable speech delivered by the Bmperor William to the reornits sworn in at Wilhelmshaven on March 9th, and only now reported, however, gives some food for reflec tion on the under currents which really direct i he situation. The treatment received by the Japaneee at the hands of the neutral Powers of the Continent has been so exceptional that it has always appeared as though the military freemasonry which controls the oonnoils of those Powers was unable to oonceive that a branch of the Yellow Raoe could be inoluded within the pale of civilisation; that,despite the perfec- tion of their naval and military organisation, the Japanese were, after all, only regarded as Dervishes with a scientific education.
THE NEED OF A BRITISH HOSPITAL. A correspondent writes to us suggesting that we should invite expressions of opinion as o the great need which many think exists for the establishment of either a British Cottage Hospital or Naming Home in Alexandria, and the possibility and advisability of taking steps in order to supply the want It will be within the recollection of our readers that this ques- tion was mooted in our columns a few months ago, at the time that attention was direoted to it by the lamented death ot a promising young Englishman from small-pox, contracted while convalescent from fever at one of onr hospitals, Nothing, however, has resalted from the oorrespondenoe that took place, and no steps have, as far as we are aware, been taken, even in the direction of the establishment of an international isolation hospital for the treatment of contagions diseases, a matter which seemed to be at the time, and impresses ns still, as being one of urgenoy. It stands, how- ever, quite apart from the question of tho establishment of a purely British hospital, and that is the subject upon which we should be glad to have the views of our readers. Every- body knows how condnoive it is to recovery for a patient to be surrounded with favorable conditions, and the feelings of contentment induced even in the ooume of a painful illness by the knowledge that dootora, names, and attendants are of one’s own nationality, are not considerations to be dismissed as of trifling aooonnt We all like our suffering ones to have every possible amelioration of their condition, and where such a question as that of the establishment of a Cottage Hospital is concerned perhaps funds would more readily flow for its erection, than for many other purely national objects,—a club or library for instanoe. We leave the matter for our readers’ consideration, and will will- ingly publish any communications on the subject with which we may be favored.
